  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework, the Temporal Mixture Density Network with Causal Dynamic Routing (TMDN-CDR), designed to model auction durations as a continuous-time stochastic process by performing sequential probabilistic forecasting of bid arrival times, while dynamically integrating game-theoretic priors and product embeddings through a causally regularized, time-varying routing mechanism. Unlike prior work—including the static SCB-MBMDN or the three-stage pipeline in Paper 3—that predicts final duration in a single forward pass, TMDN-CDR treats the auction as an unfolding marked temporal point process, where each bid constitutes an event carrying information about bidder behavior, product appeal, and market dynamics. At each bid arrival, the model updates its internal state using a recurrent transformer architecture, computes a new mixture density over the time-to-next-bid, and adjusts the relative contribution of its dual input streams—game-theoretic hazard estimates and contextual product embeddings—via a Causal Temporal Router (CTR). The CTR is a lightweight neural module that outputs time-dependent gating weights, modulated by both observed event history and high-level semantic attributes (e.g., scarcity, brand). Critically, these routing decisions are constrained by differentiable causal penalties derived from auction theory: for example, we impose that the router must increase reliance on game-theoretic signals when competition intensity (measured by bid frequency) exceeds a threshold, reflecting equilibrium refinement under pressure. These constraints are encoded as Lagrangian terms in the training objective, ensuring that learned dynamics remain economically plausible. The game-theoretic branch computes time-varying hazard functions under quantal response equilibrium, updated recursively as new bids arrive; the embedding branch uses a fine-tuned vision-language encoder (e.g., CLIP) to extract evolving desirability signals from product images and descriptions. A cross-modal attention module captures interactions between strategic and perceptual factors. The final output is a sequence of conditional duration distributions, enabling not only accurate endpoint prediction but also real-time risk assessment, early anomaly detection (e.g., bot-like bidding), and counterfactual simulation. Significance lies in unifying three paradigms—temporal point processes, causal representation learning, and dynamic multimodal fusion—into a single interpretable, adaptive architecture. Impact extends beyond e-commerce to ad exchanges, financial auctions, and mechanism design, where real-time, uncertainty-aware forecasting is critical.",
